# fedora-dev live-gate preset — PARSED (never sourced) by live-gate-run.sh's lg_load (host fallback).
# A workload may ship its own `.live-gate` at its repo top to override this (preferred, since it
# auto-tracks the run-contract). Installed to ~/.config/live-gate/fedora-dev.env by setup-user.sh.
#
# fedora-dev's run-contract MINUS public publishes (-p) MINUS real secrets MINUS real volumes.
#
# CAPS (v1.2.54): the gate launch imposes a --cap-drop=ALL floor and only adds back NAMED caps — but
# production run.sh runs under podman's DEFAULT cap set implicitly, so a fence naming only
# NET_ADMIN/SYS_ADMIN under-caps the candidate vs its own run-contract. fedora-dev's PID-1 boot needs
# the defaults: chown -R of the home volume (CHOWN/DAC_OVERRIDE/FOWNER), runuser -u core + sshd privsep
# (SETUID/SETGID/SETPCAP/SYS_CHROOT), the defensive setcap restore (SETFCAP), sshd on :22
# (NET_BIND_SERVICE), the TERM-trap/watchdog killing core-owned children (KILL). PROVEN empirically
# (2026-07-07, in-box): under drop-ALL + the 2 old adds the candidate exits <1s at the first home-volume
# op — the cause of every fedora-dev `healthy FAIL(none)` false RED. This list = podman's default set,
# named (a DELIBERATE fence declaration, per the validator's default-deny design), + the run-contract's
# NET_ADMIN/SYS_ADMIN.
CAND_FENCE='--cap-add CHOWN --cap-add DAC_OVERRIDE --cap-add FOWNER --cap-add FSETID --cap-add KILL --cap-add NET_BIND_SERVICE --cap-add SETFCAP --cap-add SETGID --cap-add SETPCAP --cap-add SETUID --cap-add SYS_CHROOT --cap-add NET_ADMIN --cap-add SYS_ADMIN --device /dev/net/tun --device /dev/fuse --security-opt label=disable'
# The image's real health-cmd (OCI drops the Containerfile HEALTHCHECK, so the gate passes it explicitly):
HEALTH='pgrep -x sshd && pgrep -x tailscaled && test -S /run/user/1000/podman/podman.sock'
# Access-path probe: the sshd door actually answers an SSH banner on :22 (run INSIDE the candidate).
# Load-bearing — stronger than the healthcheck's pgrep (a healthy-but-not-serving image fails here).
CAND_PROBE="timeout 6 bash -c 'exec 3<>/dev/tcp/127.0.0.1/22; read -t 5 -u 3 b; case \"\$b\" in SSH-*) exit 0;; *) exit 1;; esac'"
